{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 13:28:38.855123", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — bloom-filter lab (host_1, host_2, switch_1, switch_2)\nSummary\n- End-to-end IP connectivity between host_1 (10.0.0.1) and host_2 (10.0.0.2) is broken: 100% packet loss in both directions.\n- Traffic is being emitted by switch_1 toward the inter-switch port, but there is no observed reception at host_2. The failure localizes to the inter-switch path and/or switch_2 (the downstream switch).\n- Additional control-plane access and runtime visibility to switch_2 appear impaired (thrift client connections failed), limiting full diagnosis from the control plane.\n\nEvidence and observations (raw findings)\n1) Reachability / ping\n- host_1 -> host_2: 4 tx, 0 rx, 100% loss (ping_pair output).\n- get_reachability aggregated result shows host_2 -> host_1 also 100% loss.\n\n2) Host interface state\n- host_1 (10.0.0.1) eth0:\n  - state: UP, LOWER_UP\n  - TX packets: 4, RX packets: 0\n  - ip route: 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth0\n- host_2 (10.0.0.2) eth0:\n  - state: UP, LOWER_UP\n  - TX packets: 4, RX packets: 0\n  - ip route: 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth0\n- ethtool on both hosts: link detected: yes (link layer up).\n\nInterpretation: both hosts have their NICs up and are transmitting packets, but neither host is receiving traffic from the other (RX=0). That implies packets are not being delivered across the network path between the hosts.\n\n3) switch_1 (bmv2) runtime logs\n- switch_1 bmv2 logs show:\n  - The P4 pipeline is active and has LPM entries for the IPv4 destinations (10.0.0.1 and 10.0.0.2).\n  - Repeated processing of packets received on port 1 (host_1 side) and \"Transmitting packet of size 98 out of port 2\" (egress port 2 = inter-switch port). The log shows multiple packet processing cycles with egress port 2 set.\n  - Example log lines: \"Processing packet received on port 1\" -> \"Egress port is 2\" -> \"Transmitting packet ... out of port 2\".\n\nInterpretation: switch_1 receives host_1 traffic and forwards it toward port 2 (the inter-switch link) as expected by its forwarding table.\n\n4) switch_2 (bmv2) access / logs\n- Attempts to query switch_2 via the bmv2 thrift client and to dump tables failed with: \"Could not connect to thrift client on port 9090 / Make sure the switch is running and that you have the right port\".\n- The bmv2_table_dump call for switch_1 also returned thrift errors when attempted later (some thrift client errors present in the multi-tool output).\n- The multi-tool run included successful, verbose logs for switch_1 but not for switch_2 — control-plane connection to switch_2 appears unavailable (or misconfigured).\n\nInterpretation: switch_2 either is not running its bmv2 process, its thrift server is not listening/accessible on the expected port, or there is a control-plane network isolation preventing management connectivity.\n\n5) Additional log note\n- In switch logs: \"JSON input file bloom_filter.json cannot be opened\" appears. This suggests a P4 program JSON or configuration file was not found/opened at some point for at least one switch. Despite that, switch_1 shows active pipeline and LPM entries — the missing JSON message may be related to initial load attempts or a misconfiguration on one of the switches.\n\nFault localization\nBased on the evidence, the most likely fault domain is:\n- The path from switch_1 port 2 (inter-switch) to host_2 (via switch_2) — i.e., the inter-switch link and/or switch_2.\nConcrete localized items:\n- switch_1 is working (receives from host_1, forwards to port 2).\n- Traffic forwarded out of switch_1 toward switch_2 is not observed arriving at host_2 (host_2 RX = 0).\n- switch_2 is the downstream device in that path; control-plane access to switch_2 (thrift) failed — pointing to a problem with the switch_2 process or its connectivity.\n\nRoot-cause hypotheses (ranked)\n1) (High likelihood) switch_2 dataplane or control process not running or mis-bound — switch_1 forwards to the inter-switch port but switch_2 is not operating on its expected port so packets are dropped or not processed. Evidence:\n   - Could not connect to switch_2 thrift (9090).\n   - No packet RX on host_2 despite switch_1 transmitting to port2.\n2) (High likelihood) Inter-switch link or port mapping problem — the link between switch_1:eth1 and switch_2:eth1 could be down, miswired, or mapped to different port indices in the bmv2 runtime so switch_1 sends into a non-connected port. Evidence:\n   - switch_1 shows egress on port2, but host_2 and switch_2 show no sign of receipt.\n   - Hosts report link detected, but that does not guarantee that the switch-to-switch patch is connected at the expected logical ports.\n3) (Medium likelihood) P4 program / JSON misconfiguration on one or both switches (bloom_filter.json missing on at least one device), causing inconsistent forwarding behavior. Evidence:\n   - Log line: \"JSON input file bloom_filter.json cannot be opened\".\n   - However switch_1 appears to be executing a pipeline and has LPM entries, so if misconfiguration exists it may be partial or only on switch_2.\n4) (Lower likelihood) Host NIC or guest environment issue on host_2 blocking RX (e.g., kernel firewall), but this is less likely because:\n   - Both switch_1 logs show egress and host_2 shows TX but no RX.\n   - The more probable issue is mid-path (switch_2 or link) rather than both hosts having symmetric firewall drops.\n\nConfidence levels\n- Observed connectivity failure (hosts): high confidence (100% packet loss).\n- switch_1 behavior (receives and forwards to port2): high confidence (bmv2 logs).\n- switch_2 control-plane unreachable (thrift errors): high confidence (thrift errors returned).\n- Root cause (switch_2 or inter-switch link): moderate-to-high confidence (consistent with logs and hosts RX counters).\n- P4 JSON missing as contributor: moderate confidence (explicit message in logs).\n\nData gaps / things that prevented definitive isolation\n- No successful runtime logs or counters from switch_2 (couldn't connect to thrift). Without switch_2 packet logs or counters, we cannot tell whether switch_2 is receiving the frames and failing to forward them, or not receiving them at all.\n- No sniff or packet capture on the inter-switch link to prove whether frames egressing switch_1 appear on the physical link.\n- No bmv2 table/counter dumps from switch_2 to determine the mapping of ports to interfaces on that switch and whether the P4 pipeline is loaded and active there.\n\nRecommended next diagnostic data to collect (for completeness; not mitigation)\n- Retrieve logs and table/counter dumps from switch_2 (bmv2) — confirm that the switch process is running and that the P4 program is loaded.\n- Capture packets on the inter-switch link (switch_1 eth1 / switch_2 eth1) or run a packet capture on the host connected to that link, to see whether frames egressing switch_1 actually arrive at the other end.\n- Check the mapping of port numbers to interfaces on both switches (ensure switch_1 port2 corresponds to the physical cable to switch_2 and vice versa).\n- Verify that bloom_filter.json (or the compiled P4 JSON) was loaded successfully on switch_2 and check for any errors during startup.\n- If possible, re-run bmv2_get_log and bmv2_table_dump on switch_2 once its thrift server is reachable.\n\nConclusion\n- The network is currently unhealthy: hosts cannot reach each other (100% loss).\n- The immediate fault localizes to the downstream side of the path (inter-switch link and/or switch_2). switch_1 is forwarding packets toward switch_2 but there is no evidence of arrival at host_2.\n- The most probable causes are: switch_2 bmv2 process not running or inaccessible, or a wiring/port-mapping issue on the inter-switch link. A P4 configuration file error was observed in logs and may be a contributing factor on one of the switches.\n\n(End of report)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12960, "output_tokens": 3421, "total_tokens": 16381, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12032}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1536}}}
